                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-10</span>
                    </div>
                    <span> This film is an excellent (although depressing) look at the "fair and balanced" FOX news. The idea behind the whole thing is this: Pretend that ALL the news channels are liberally biased. Pretend that you are 'balancing" that problem by this: two heads, each with a point of view, yelling at each other. This has worked very well for him. A LOT of Americans think this mess is "fair and balanced". This film is a fine illustration of the sickening truth. Here's the future of American "news" :two heads hollering. No matter WHAT the issue, there must be two points of view. "Here with an opposing view, please welcome Benito."</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Pointed sensationalism</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-04</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This skillfully-crafted film uses the same propaganda techniques it exposes to illustrate the overwhelming bias machine that is Fox News.  Although it may be propaganda, that does not dismiss the content.  Much of it still rings true to intelligent, educated viewers.  This film offers the best in the documentary tradition:  It educates, informs, and challenges.  Even when viewers disagree with the film's conclusions, we may still enjoy the clarity and provocative nature of a presentation that respects our intelligence.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A bit disappointing</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-02</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I first became interested in the issue of biased journalism after reading Al Franken's "Lies and the Lying Liars who Tell Them."  It touched upon the hypocrisy of the Fox News Network.  I was intrigued, so I waited to see this documentary with much anticipation.  
<br />
<br />While I have respect for the vast amount of research, the hours upon hours of tapes that went into making this documentary, I have problems with how it was edited.  The filmmakers interviewed many credible people, and when someone would make an incriminating statement against Fox, footage from the news network is shown to support the statement.  The problem, however, is that the footage would be just a few seconds, and therefore difficult to know what kind of context it was taken from.  They would also use ten or twenty different examples of similar footage (for example of bill o'reilly saying "shut up") to get the point across.  while this editing style is amusing at first, it gets overused and repititious.
<br />
<br />The documentary would be more credible if instead of using twenty 1-second shots, it spent more time on a few and allowed us to see what was happening in context.  As it is, the documentary is just full of opinions, and dare I say, no less biased than fox.</span>
                  
              
